The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Fares of taxis, buses, minibuses, trams and ferries will increase from Monday. The minimum fare in case of taxis is Rs 20, which will go up by Rs 1.70 for every subsequent 200 metres. Buses will charge a minimum of Rs 4 and minibuses Rs 4.50. Fares of city buses will go up by 50 paise at every subsequent stage. For ferries and trams, too, the minimum fares and the fares for every subsequent stage will go up by 50 paise.

 Eastern Railway (ER) will run two more Puja specials between Sealdah and New Jalpaiguri on October 7 and 8. The Down train will leave New Jalpaiguri on October 7 and the Up train will leave Sealdah on October 8. ER has also made arrangements to run 18 more Sealdah-Jaipur trains in the festive season.

 Rajendra Fatehchand, a factory owner, was arrested on Saturday night for illegally printing the logo of a firm on the packets of his products. Fatehchand?s factory is at Chanditala, Hooghly. The owners of a firm at 46, BB Ganguly Street had lodged a complaint with Bowbazar police station, alleging that Fatehchand, a Howrah resident, had been illegally using their logo.

 Calcutta Medical Research Institute launched an ?advanced clinic? for women last week. Medical superintendent Mala Chattopadhay said the clinic was equipped to handle all kinds of health problems faced by women. 

 Singapore Airlines has announced a Hong Kong Disneyland holiday offer, including a stopover in Singapore. The airfare, excluding taxes, is Rs 16,999 (in the economy class). Starting at $28 a night, the Singapore stopover comes with hotel accommodation, free entry to tourist spots like Jurong Bird Park and Sentosa Island, and select discounts. The promotion is valid for sale till 8 October for travel from Calcutta. 

 The Rotary Club of New Ballygunge, in association with Royal Nepalese Consulate, honoured Pandit Gopal Lal Shrestha at Kala Kunj on Sunday. Pandit Shrestha is an exponent of classical music, thumri, ghazal and bhajan. The felicitation was part of the India-Nepal Friendship Festival.

 West Bengal Assembly Speaker Hashim Abdul Halim inaugurated a showroom of products by women?s self-help groups in Barasat, on the northern fringes of the city, on Sunday. State finance minister Asim Dasgupta, state health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra and Rajya Sabha member Brinda Karat attended the programme. 

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee inaugurated a swimming pool at Jadavpur Kishore Bharati Stadium on Sunday evening. The 6th National Swimming Championship for the Disabled is being held at the pool. Mayor Bikash Bhattacharya, Lok Sabha Speaker Somnath Chatterjee and Sunderbans affairs minister Kanti Ganguly were among those who attended the programme. The championship will continue till October 6.

